shared_text:
Governor Phil Murphy
April 16 at 1:20 PM ·

BREAKING: Our public schools will remain closed through at least Friday, May 15th.

We need to be guided by where the facts on the ground, science, and public health take us. That means it will not be safe to reopen our schools for at least another four weeks.

I’ve made this decision in careful consultation with New Jersey Department of Health and New Jersey Department Of Education, among other key stakeholders.

I know this is hard. But we are saving lives and we must maintain the course.

post_text:
Hello Parents & Happy Halloween Eve! 🎃

Due to the grim forecast we are preparing for a parade in wet weather. 🌧☔ If it is raining at the scheduled time of our parade we will be having the parade in the front of the school along the sidewalk from the area of the library to the front entrance. We are asking for any parents who would be willing and able to bring and set up Easy-Up Tents in front of the school along the sidewalk areas so that the children can have their parade without getting their costumes wet. We believe we will need about 15 Easy-Up tents to be set up by 1pm from the entrance in front of the library to the front door.
We are asking parents and staff not to park in the front parking spaces to allow parents to line up and watch the parade.

Thank you so much in advance for your help and understanding! We look forward to seeing you all tomorrow to watch the witches, monsters, heroes, and all other Halloween Friends show off their costumes during the parade.

-- Nokomis School Staff

post_text: Nokomis had a very special visitor today! A "fence lizard" was seen climbing on the outside wall of the school! The eastern fence lizard is a medium-sized species of lizard. The species is found along forest edges, rock piles, and rotting logs or stumps in the eastern United States. We hope to see Noki the Nokomis Lizard again soon!

post_text: In Library, our third graders have been learning how to do research on the internet. Our focus was World Ocean Day which is June 8, 2019. The third graders began by exploring websites. After they located a specific website, they waded into the ocean-related content. They dove in deeper to learn about the impact of trash on marine life. Then the students each developed an Ocean Slogan designed to lure people in and created a beach bottle to highlight the importance of keeping our oceans clean. The Beach Bottles are currently on display in the library.

Jenna would like to attend the University of Hawaii to become a Marine Biologist. After college, Jenna plans to work at a university with a Marine Biology program. She would like to research coral reefs, deep trenches, specific animals and microscopic organisms! Great job, Jenna! Lookout world, here comes class of 2026!

post_text: Third grade naturalists Read "A Tree Is Growing" and went outside to identify and label different plants and animals that are coming out in spring! We discovered Sweet Gum Tree Seeds, a variety of pine cones, hardened sap, and even found the first flowers of spring! The kids did leaf rubbings of our treasures, and even wrote nature poems inspired by Robert Frost!
